Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist1:Thought: My motivation stems from the growing need for more structured, interpretable, and user-controllable image editing in diffusion models—especially as they scale toward real-world creative applications. While recent works have explored adaptive context modeling (Paper 1), fine-grained motion editing via text (Paper 2), and interpretability of text encoders (Paper 3), a critical gap remains: how to explicitly learn and manipulate *semantic flows*—structured trajectories in latent space that correspond to meaningful, disentangled visual transformations (e.g., "add glasses," "age face by 10 years," "change lighting direction"). Most editing methods rely on post-hoc manipulation or require paired data, limiting composability and accumulation. Transformer-based Flow Matching models offer a unique opportunity because they model continuous-time dynamics with high expressivity and can be conditioned on rich cross-attention mechanisms. By designing a framework that *learns structured semantic flows as explicit, reusable operators* in the latent space, we can enable composable, accumulative edits without retraining. This differs from prior work by not only analyzing latent representations (as in Diffusion Lens) but actively structuring them into *actionable flow fields* governed by linguistic semantics. The key innovation lies in decoupling edit semantics from content generation through a dual-path transformer architecture that separates *base generation* from *flow injection*, enabling plug-and-play editing modules.

